If I gave Jin Ramen in Harlem, three stars, then I have to give Totto Ramen four. I feel like it's hard for me to rate this place because there are SO MANY delicious ramen joints in California. Just in my neighborhood in SoCal, there are at least three or four decent places and the waits are not typically long at all (if there even is a wait). But the standards since I've been in NYC seem to be different, so the rating is relative to the city. The first time I tried this place was on my birthday. I had been doing some reporting that went late into the night. Friend and I came here because I wanted noodles on my birthday (as per Chinese tradition). It was past 10 pm when we arrived and it was sprinkling wet and cold. The wait for two of us was over an hour. I ordered the miso ramen with pork and she ordered the chicken ramen with spicy sauce on the side. ? The broth here is chicken broth, not tonkatsu pork broth. I tend to like the richness of tonkatsu while eating ramen. But after trying Totto Ramen twice, it's nice to have the lighter (chicken) broth as well. I guess I have come to appreciate it after becoming so accustomed to tonkatsu. For both times, I didn't find the texture of the noodles to be too soft or hard. They were chewy in the right amounts. I enjoyed the (half) egg that came with my miso ramen--too bad it wasn't a full egg! My pork slices were surprisingly tough to break apart though, which really disappointed me. I was overall expecting more, especially with the long wait. But my friend (who doesn't eat much ramen) really really LOVED hers. It really made her happy, and afterward she was dying to go again. She also mentioned wanting to bring her family. The second time, I came with the same friend, also later at night at 9:30 pm. She had wanted to come so I figured this was my chance to give it another shot. The wait was about 30 minutes (so not bad at all for Totto wait-time averages). But then again, it was snowing and sprinkling outside...sleet. She ordered the same, and I ordered spicy Totto ramen this time, and with chicken. Because I was particularly hungry, I also ordered the avo-tuna for an appetizer, which came out almost immediately. The avo-tuna was delicious, particularly the seared tuna sashimi. Some portions were too drenched in soy sauce though (like the avocado), making it taste too salty. If they had just been a bit neater or easier on the sauce, the dish would have been perfect! I also enjoyed the minced garlic on the side. I would order the dish again if I'm craving some sashimi with my ramen. I was surprised that my spicy ramen was tastier than I remembered my miso ramen to be. I'm not sure if it was just because of the rayu hot sauce or because of a different broth, or maybe both. The slices of chicken were surprisingly tender, which I appreciated! They were better than the pork I had the first time. I think I had read some reviews to get the pork, but I actually felt like the chicken was better. I realized today (the day after the meal), that I didn't have an egg with my ramen. So I guess that's one-minus for ordering the spicy Totto ramen rather than the miso ramen. I enjoy this place, but again, I'm wary (and weary) of the long waits...particularly because I don't think this would happen in California. But I think I would come yet again if I were craving ramen because there aren't as many (good) ramen options in NY, particularly midtown and above (at least not that I know of right now). And the wait is still shorter than Ippudo, whose wait is an entirely different story...
