Japanese cuisine is by far my favorite type of cuisine, so I've had my share of ramen in the states I've lived in: New York and Hawaii (which is essentially New Japan). Totto ramen is among the best I've had. Had both the niku and paitan bowls, and I prefer the latter. (The niku became overwhelmingly heavy with sodium toward the end of the bowl -- I feared for my blood pressure at that point.) The ramen noodles are delightfully chewy, the broth perfectly seasoned, but what sets Totto apart for me is the pork: quickly blow torched to juicy, slightly crispy-on-the-outside perfection. The price is fair, in my opinion. Another plus is the intimate, hole-in-the-wall atmosphere. I love sitting at the counter and watching the chefs, who so clearly enjoy their jobs that they sing while sifting through noodles and wear adorable "I Heart Ramen" tees, prepare my food. Unfortunately, the trade-off for this level of intimacy is a long waiting line. I recommend coming here around 5:30pm for dinner lest you burn through one to two hours for a bowl of Totto ramen. (And yes, you should be present for the entire wait because they are not very forgiving about seating you if you're not present when your name is called.) I also advise against parties with odd numbers of people -- priority will always go to parties of two (and consequently, multiples thereof). Two of my friends and I once made the mistake of coming here on a Friday at 7pm, only to have to wait an excruciating two and a half hours for our food. Let's just say we cycled through a range of emotional extremes. Another menu highlight: char siu mayo don with yuzu mayo if you're hankering for more blow-torched meaty goodness.
