Totto is a really small Japanese noodle restaurant that has an incredibly long wait for a seat almost all the time. And no, you cannot make reservations. Why the heck would you want to go to a place like this? Well, it's really all about the ramen, and if you haven't heard about it, then I don't know where you've been. It's unbelievably good, and they have the ramen down to a science. There has always been the long debate about which restaurant serves the best ramen in the city. So far, Totto has my #1 vote on this. It's also actually voted as having the best ramen in NYC. Why is that? Well, I'm not going to spill too many of the details because that would only spoil the surprise. You're going to have to come to Totto one day, endure the long line, and discover for yourself what the ridiculous hype is about. Yes, when I say long line, there is a long line. You might want to get a coffee because it's going to be a long, intolerable wait unless you come here during lunch early in the week. I'm not a big fan of long times, and this is probably one of the worst lines I've endured (outside) for food. If I could do it though, you can most certainly do it. The first time I was here with my husband, it was a cold below 30 degrees outside in the middle of December, and I'm waiting in line for a stinking bowl of ramen. There are at least 25 people ahead of me. The wait system; you scribble your name down on a clipboard, and the waiter comes out every 15-20 minutes to call out the next guest in line. Luckily they have an enclosed area by the entrance so you're not standing entirely outside. You unfortunately may have to suffer watching the customers already inside slurping down their ramen. Finally, 2 hours later, toes almost frozen and fingers numb, my name was called. When you enter, you're greeted by a friendly Japanese waiter and the aromas of ramen. It helps that they have Japanese waiters/cooks here because that shows the authenticity. The menu is not large and is strictly focused on ramen selections, but there is a minimal selection of small side dishes that you can order. One thing to note though is that you better bring cash because it's cash only here. Since I love spicy food, I had to get the Totto Spicy Ramen which is actually one of their most popular choices on the menu. This ramen has a spicy sesame oil added to their original Paitan ramen. The original Totto Chicken Paitan Ramen has homemade noodles cooked al dente style in a whole chicken and soy sauce based soup topped with ingredients like scallion and char siu pork. My husband and I also order a side of the char siu pork buns to start it off. If you score a seat at the bar/counter in front of the cooks, you can witness the ramen lab in action. I like to call it a lab because they really do cook the food like it's science. They have giant steaming pots of chicken broth and endless slabs of pork. They filter the heck out of that broth and stir the heck out of it with a giant wooden paddle. They grab a blowtorch and blowtorch the heck out of that already juicy looking pork. After we place our orders, we turn around and our ramen and pork buns are already in front of us. It looks amazing, like pictures depict. The first bite into the pork buns is like taking a bite into heaven. There are not too many foods out there where I can say this. The bun itself is super soft, and the pork is the perfect level of chewiness. My husband and I dig our chopsticks into our ramen and slurp up the broth. The one thing about Totto ramen that makes it assuredly amazing is the broth. 95% of what makes the ramen work so well is the chicken-based broth they use. It's quite creamy and flavorful, rich in whatever magical ingredients they are using. It's also surprisingly very clean. Their aren't globs of some oils or mysterious floating elements in this broth. They filtered the broth numerous, endless times so it comes to you in its most clean but rich form. There is also the char siu pork and scallions sitting in the broth that adds color, texture and added flavor. The noodles are in a perfect wavy form and made al dente. The broth is surprisingly not too spicy though. Even for people who may not like spicy food will find the broth to be rather mild. I actually think it might have a needed kick that the Paitan ramen doesn't have, but I have yet to try the original ramen to determine any difference. As much as I want to sit there and enjoy hours of ramen, the experience lasts for only 15-20 minutes. You'll be surprised by how fast you eat because it's so good. Was it worth the 2 hour wait though? Without a doubt. I came here with a lot of speculation and doubt, but once I took a sip of that broth and a bite into that noodle, I was a fan. Highly recommend you give Totto a try if you have not. Just make sure you come here with some cash, a not too empty stomach, and a lot of patience.
