In a just world, there would be six of these tiny ramen houses all in a row, each interchangeable with the other because when you're jonesing for homestyle ramen, any shop should do, right? But this is not the Ginza, it's the Theater District, and luckily, Totto Ramen does it right thanks to owner Bobby Munekata's focus on the quality of the broth and the freshness of the ingredients. Truth be told, it's not quite up to the platinum standards set by Ippudo and Momofuku Noodle Bar, but the hearty goodness compares favorably to just about anyone else in Manhattan serving ramen. And since there aren't five other ramen houses nearby competing for business, Totto appears to be a magnet for the Yelperati and masses of Japanese tourists looking for a taste of home. Be prepared to wait as the place is beyond tiny - a row of counter stools, a table for two and another for four. That's all I could see through the crowd after waiting for a blessedly brief twenty minutes out on the steps with the rest of the hungry noodle slurper wannabes. Once seated at the counter, I perused the small menu, which presents a choice of seven ramen bowls - plus quite an array of toppings and appetizers. I decided to go full gonzo and order the $15.50 Mega Ramen billed as the bowl "for Char Siu Lover", i.e., extra pork for the porkers among us (see photo). The chicken broth was velvety-tasty and not too salty. Topped with several slices of char siu pork, the bowl also features a mound of shredded pork, minced garlic, onion, bean sprouts and julienned scallions. The true test is the quality of the homemade noodles, and they had that perfectly al dente texture and a flavor steeped in chicken and soy sauce that truly marks a genuine ramen noodle. Flat-out delicious. As a side, I went for the $4 Pickled Japanese Cucumber, which looked nothing like the picture in the menu insert. It was just a straightforward cucumber peeled, pickled and sliced and topped with shredded nori. It provided a fresh crunchy nosh that complemented the savory ramen broth. Gee, I think I was done in about twenty minutes, which was just as well since there was a growing army forming outside waiting to get in like a scene from "Soylent Green". Alas, I exited wondering why there can't be more ramen houses like this in San Francisco much less Manhattan. FOOD - 4 stars...really solid working-class ramen nicely executed AMBIANCE - 3 stars...it's a subterranean walk-in closet SERVICE - 4 stars...really attentive...they have to be to turn their waiting list around with haste TOTAL - 4 stars...tiny, high-quality ramen house that I wish was in my neighborhood
