Ever since I was a young child, I loved ramen. My mom used to cook it in a pot with poached egg, vegetables, and Chinese sausage. Starting in college, ramen ceased to be a nice meal, but instead, became a late night comfort food that would tide me through the last ten pages of my paper or few hours of studying. It also made for a cheap, yet delicious meal. But once I moved to New York, my friends started telling me about gourmet ramen cafes and I started seeing them all around town. Totto Ramen seems to be the legendary place to check out so a couple of friends and I came here for dinner on Tuesday. From down the street, you can see Totto Ramen. Not because it's a big place, but rather, because there are an insane number of people waiting outside. Optimistic that the line would move quickly, we added our names to the list around 6:30. The host said it would only be an hour. 30 minutes pass by and we're still pumped. An hour and we're really pumped. An hour and a half we're starving and considering going elsewhere. Two hours and we're grumpy and really annoyed that the line seems to have not moved. The chefs seem to sense our impatience (or are intimidated by the fact that we're standing right by the door almost glaring at the happy people slowly eating their ramen) and apologize for the wait, but since it's such a small spot, all we can do is wait. Finally we are in! We start off with the Char Siu Pork Buns, which had field greens and tartar sauce in it. It was interesting and my friend and I agreed that it might cater more for people who didn't grow up eating pork buns, especially because of the tartar sauce. I then had the Totto Spicy Ramen with pork, which was delicious! The noodles were perfectly cooked and the broth was amazing! Not very spicy, but peppery and with lots of scallions, just the way I like it. Yum! My one complaint was that the pork meat was super fatty, which I'm personally not a fan of but it made my friend happy. I got full after eating half the bowl but it was so good I couldn't stop. All in all, Totto Ramen did not disappoint. I'll be back, but I would definitely not wait another two hours to get food. People mentioned that something in the kitchen was broken which is why the wait was so long, but the host could've said something instead of telling everyone that it would only take an hour max. I now understand the Totto Ramen hype and can't wait to come back (and maybe next time, if my wait is shorter, I'll add a star to my rating)!
