Totto Ramen is deserving of its title as one of the best ramen joints in NYC. The atmosphere here feels just like the way ramen joints should authentically be: casual, quick, unpretentious, and incredibly fulfilling. Started with the broiled char siu pork. The pork was wonderfully grilled with the aromas of a high-grade charcoal grill. There was a nice ratio of meat to fat, which was marbleized nicely. The presentation was simple with a touch of slightly sweet sauce over a bed of veggies, which served to highlight the quality of the pork slices. Had the much-hyped spicy chicken paitan ramen next. The broth was superb. It was not as rich as a tonkotsu pork bone broth, but then again chicken bone broth is not supposed to resemble that. Instead, it had a umami-filled yet light flavour with a really clean and pure chicken essence that tasted of free-range chicken without any MSG added. The rayu (chili sesame oil) gave the broth a nice kick as a complement, with hints of a Chinese-influenced peppercorn type of spiciness. The noodles were thinner than most I've had, although thinner noodles are a better complement to chicken only broths compared to the richer pork bone broths. Nevertheless, they were cooked as perfectly al dente as they can be. No complaints here. The toppings for the ramen were basic but solid. The egg was perfectly poached to a liquid-y perfection. The nori was unfortunately soaked in the broth which made it lose its crunch. I liked how the green onions were cut nice and long to cut out the richness of the broth. The chicken pieces lacked flavour though and appeared to be simply for producing the broth rather than eaten as a topping. Totto Ramen makes an amazing chicken bone broth ramen with a Chinese spice twist at reasonable prices (basically much cheaper than Ippudo). The two types of ramen are so different that the two are hardly comparable, but I will say that Totto does its specialty better than Ippudo does theirs. Definitely a must try for ramen in NYC despite the waits! - Roger the Pig
