I dropped in to check out this Japanese ramen hot spot on one muggy afternoon. Lawrence L and several of my foodie friends had raved about this place so naturally I had to find out where they stand in the line of ramen giants like Santouka and Daikokuya. I was hoping to skip the wait since the humidity was almost unbearable. To my surprise, the wait was still very long as many of the people came with the same idea in mind. Interested diner should first look for the wait list located on the front door upon arrival. They don't have a wait area so the line usually requires one to hangout by the narrow sidewalk with a view of their open kitchen where each bowl of ramen was assembled before they are handed out to the tables. The venue is small, rustic, dark, with dispositions of a perfect ramen hole in the wall. There was a line of people that sat at the counter facing the chefs while others rubbed elbows at the tightly arranged wooden tables on the other side of the wall. I ordered the Totto Spicy Ramen ($10.75) that came with al dente egg noodles, thick and creamy pork broth, spicy sesame oil, thin and long slices of scallions, char siu pork, bean sprouts and nori. I then added a soft-boiled egg ($1) and firm bamboo ($1) for additional flavors and textures. I don't believe ramen should ever cost more than $10 a bowl but it was well worth it. The egg noodles could use more flavor but it embodied an excellent bite and texture. The broth had an excellent baseline of pork flavor with lifts and depths underscored by a rich and striking garlic and black pepper in every sip. ?I loved the addition of bamboo as they were plentiful, firm, fresh and moist. The egg was a bit more well done than expected but it was still superior than those provided at Santouka. Comparatively, the support cast was superior to the likes of Daikokuya and Santouka on the counts of freshness and texture. They gave the broth a nice lift on the flavors but it was a bit too salty towards the end. This became evident when the black pepper flavor emerged from the background and started to dominate the broth at the bottom of the bowl. The broth was not as creamy as Daikokuya and Santouka, but the pork flavor was superior to go along with thick, succulent char siu pork that was clearly the best I have come across. Lastly, I also appreciated the rayu, or chili oil, as the level of spiciness nicely complemented the broth without hijacking it. In light of all the 5-stars qualities, I had to be able to finish the broth in order to consider this place the best of the best. Unfortunately, the strong black pepper flavor at the end had precluded me from completing such mission but all else was truly excellent. Service was friendly, responsive, quick and efficient in light of the persistent crowd in and outside of the restaurant. I have come to terms with the price, and believe this is one of the must visit places for ramen enthusiasts. I would absolutely love to come back again. Cash only.
