First, a disclaimer: My breakdown of ramen places is considerably different than how I would evaluate any other restaurant, and is as follows: - 70% Broth - 15% Other Ramen Components - 15% Other Stuff (Price, Environment, Service, etc.) Totto gets a 80% from me. In actuality, it's probably closer to 85%, but I'm rather limited by the integer-based star rating that Yelp allows me. I met my friend here Thursday night for a quick dinner after work. Although I don't find myself heading north of 34th Street since I've moved downtown, this was one place that is definitely worth the trek up. On 52nd and 9th Avenue, Totto is fairly easy to get to via subway. Although the entrance is small and easily passable, you can spot the location nearly a block away thanks to the perpetual line of people waiting outside. At a little after 7PM, the line was only about 6 or 7 people long; as a warning though: after I left around 8PM, it had nearly doubled. So, plan your dinner accordingly. There are a smattering of tables and bar seats, and pretty much only one narrow strip of floor for both servers and clients to walk on. Needless to say, it's crammed and it's bound to get warm, especially during the summer. Once you've put your name on the waitlist and finally get to the front of the line, you'll be seated depending on your party size (smaller is better) and the seating availability. My friend and I opted for a table, but if you do get seated by the bar, you can actually see the chefs making your ramen. The menu is small and straightforward - you can opt for some starters/appetizers like pork buns or fried rice, but the main attraction is the ramen, of course. While my friend decided on the regular Chicken Paitan Ramen, I wanted to try their version of the Spicy Ramen. (As a heads up, they also do offer an Extra Spicy Ramen, but I would caution the likelihood that the pepper would completely overpower the nuances of flavor in the broth.) Our orders were taken quickly, cups of ice water were brought to our table, and we waited in anticipation. I don't know if there's anything quite as glorious as a steaming, aromatic bowl of ramen, especially on a chilly day. Our bowls were delivered promptly, and they were nearly picture-perfect: three slices of pork belly with fresh scallions and bean sprouts, neatly placed over a rich, opaque broth and finished off with a sheet of nori. The broth was mind-blowing; despite being chicken-based, it almost bordered on being creamy, but not as cloying as a pork-based broth. You could tell it had been simmered for a substantial amount of time, and the seasonings were pretty much spot-on. The generous spoonful (or two) of chili oil made it even more delicious, though it did change the flavor profile of the broth substantially more than expected. The toppings were adequate, the bean sprouts fresh and crunchy, and the pork belly fatty and nicely seared. The noodles, on the other hand, could have used some improvement; they didn't quite have the "chew" I was hoping for and too closely resembled the ramen noodles you'd buy in bulk back in college. Service was okay as well; I would have liked my water to be refilled at least once, but we were treated courteously and were in and out in half an hour. So would I come back? Yes, but just for that broth.
