ight ramen noodles with Char siu pork, scallions, bean sprouds, and nori with a spicy kick. Totto Chicken Paitan Ramen - Straight ramen noodles in a chicken-based broth with char siu pork, scallion, onions and nori. Niku Ramen - Ramen with TONS of pork meat! with onions, bean sprouts, and scallions. ? Totto Miso Ramen - Wavy ramen noodles in a miso broth with char siu pork, hardboiled egg, scallion, and bean sprouts. Being a spicy fan myself, I liked the Totto Spicy Ramen the most, it has a good kick of spiciness. ?You are also able to get an extra spicy version. ?Not as many places have an option for ramen in a chicken broth, and I was also a fan of the chicken paitan ramen. ?The chicken taste with pork added a good combination of flavor. ?They also have vegetable ramen for you vegetarians out there and cold ramen if you want to change it up. As for the extra toppings they offer, I usually like getting extra Char siu pork, bamboo shoots, and a boiled egg. ?You cannot go wrong with a boiled egg in your ramen! ?I am also a fan of char siu pork so I usually tend to order extra pork when I go to a ramen restaurant. ?If you sit by the bar area, you'll see they use a blowtorch to cook the pork, which adds a good little visual while you are casually chatting and eating your meal. Even though this place is very small, the turn around is pretty fast. ?Try to know what you want to order when you sit down since you have been waiting for so long already. ?Once you order, your ramen should come within just 5-10 minutes max. ?The service is quick and to the point. ?With it being a small place, it is easy to flag down a server if you have to for a drink refill or kaedama (extra order of noodles, and yes you can do that here!). ? Solid tasting ramen with a long wait for it, but hey, at least it's in NYC, there are tons of things you can do around the city while you wait, just don't miss your spot on line when they call you!
