ADHD Snap Shot: ?5 for the food 5 for the seated service, 1.5 for everything else. Make sure to get the appetizers. Totto Ramen brought even my most avid, mild mannered, Noodle Soup addiction supporter bf to his limits (beyond his limits) on patience and willingness to suffer for good food. ?Even mention of how I should rate, appears to bring back war veteran, shell shock-like agitation. ?Hence, I struggled on the rating and settled on a 4 as I think - given adequate strategery and expectation management the food can overcome some of these downsides. ?But seriously, Yelpers.... you need a plan of attack. This is where you use the Yelp website to create a master plan on how to approach dining at this restaurant. ? First the food: ?Absolutely excellent! ?To give you a sense for how excellent the food is, my bf, traumatized by the dining experience, lobbied hard to get my rating all the way down to a 1 based solely on atmosphere. I just couldn't in good conscious do it. ?The food is actually that good.The Ramen broth is amazing. ?The noodles were excellent al dente, The mix of stuff is fantastic. I added an egg, but also suggest adding corn to the Spicy Ramen with Pork. For those considering the Extra Spicy, Single Spicy was spicy enough that my bf said it was perfect and I was indifferent as to whether I should continue adding (both of us can take pretty spicy). We also got the Cod Roe rice bowl (not on menu), seaweed salad (not on Menu), and the Avo Tuna. The seaweed salad was ok (you can skip this). But the other two were delicious. ?Incidentally, the girl two seats down from us got a spicy tuna and rice dish (not on the menu). Here's the "take-away" yelpers. It is a mistake to only eat the Ramen here. ?You should and have to try the appetizers. ?If you only have the ramen, the grouchiness of the wait will stick these noodles around a 3 out of spite (they are a 5 if no wait), but the appetizers accentuate the experience and really highlight how much talent is involved at this lovely noodle shop. ?The noodle soup is filling enough, but I'm sure after the wait, stomach room is easy enough to find for these must try apps. The Wait: I signed up at 8:40pm on Friday night and was not seated until 10:30pm. Ouch... They have very strict policies at Totto. ?You have to be there when they call you. ?If you are not there, you are skipped and go to the end of the clip board. ?They also stop taking names at some point. ?Around 10pm, they count the final names and then do a calculation of how many they can serve and still close effectively at 11:00. ?You either do or do not make the cut. My advise is not to put your name in after 9pm. The Atmosphere: ?The first 3 seats at the bar are no good during the winter. Don't even bother taking your jacket or hat off. You're going to need them. ?The problem is adequate ventilation. ?The door to Totto Ramen has to be open or else this place will turn into a humid swamp of ramen. ?For me, that's not so bad... I kind of like the idea of bathing in ramen miso broth like air. ?But I think other would take issue.Additionally, there is a big fan right next to you circulating the cold air into the kitchen, and around your eating area. In the cold of winter, I suggest taking the hit of waiting longer and trying to get a seat farther back on the bar. ?if you have a group of 4 (btw... groups greater than 4 will need to be separated), then try to get the tables in the back. Also - ladies... there is no place to put your purse at the bar. ?Really. you're squeezed in and they have not installed hooks underneath the bar - as far as I can see. ?You've got to put it in your lap and balance precariously on a fairly uncomfortable bar stool. ?Realize though... this is 4 stars even though I loathe this ?kind of unthoughtful seating. ?Once the appetizers arrived I could care less. Service: My love of process and efficiency can't rate this aspect of the place anything under a 5. Wow, Totto Ramen. You guys know how to serve people quickly. ?If - during your massive wait - you are ready to order, then they are ready to take your order as soon as you sit - which - I contend - is greatly appreciated by those waiting. The wait staff and chefs are the absolute nicest. ?Seatings do tend to be in lumps - given the nature of things. The chefs are like a machine to watch. Even the best companies could learn something by watching them work together as a team. Final Details: ?Super cheap aps at around $5, noodle soup is the typical $10-15, but worth adding the extra $1-2 for extra stuff like egg and corn. ?Also... yes... this is a long review, but you've got long wait ahead of you, if you're in line reading this :)....
