Awesome! Now that denying the arrival of winter is no longer feasible it's time to explore the avenues in which one can reasonably keep warm despite snowstorms and below freezing temperatures. Sure, staying indoors wrapped in a cozy blanket with a hot cocoa in hand is always a good option. But for those who prefer not to turn into a temporary hermit ramen houses are an ideal venue for getting together with friends. In most of Japan ramen is a quick meal. You'll find ramen shops near train stations where commuters will have a bowl on their way home after a long day at work. Often these places won't even have seating. All you see is a line of 'salary men' in their business suits behind a low curtain hungrily slurping down steaming bowls of noodles. And then there are cities like Hakata, where ramen making is an art form and ramen houses are destinations. Tonkotsu ramen is one of Hakata's claims to fame and it is this flavorful pork bone based broth that has become widely popular even in New York. There are talks of Ippudo opening a Midtown location but until then Totto Ramen on the west and Hide-chan Ramen on the east serve the best ramen north of Ippudo. And in some ways, Totto Ramen, more so than Ippudo, evokes the typical ramen experience from Japan. Unlike the flashy interior of Ippudo, Totto is cramped and rustic, so much so that the steam from the kitchen practically serves as the restaurant's main source of heating. Here the star is chicken instead of pork and the resulting broth is lighter, smoother, but equally flavorful and satisfying. The wait on any given evening will be more than an hour and the best strategy would be to sign up for a table and hang out at a nearby bar while you wait. Despite this, a bowl of Totto's spicy ramen is undeniably worth waiting for. Aside from these three ramen houses in New York, there are many more that have popped up in the last few years. Some can trace their roots from Japan and some rely on its celebrity chef for its popularity. But only these three deserve to be mentioned among the best. So take advantage of the cold weather and check out each mentioned in this list. Only then do you have the right to name which ramen spot you judge to be best. For more info, check out my blog listed on my profile!
