I'm thinkin' Totto Ramen wanted me to make sweet, sweet love to my noodles because they were pumpin' some Goddamn sexy, baby-makin' R&B joints from the '90s in there. You could've told me our waitress was in one of those shiny pajama numbers with the one button buttoned a la that TLC "Creep" video, and that the dudes behind the ramen bar were actually those puppets from Blackstreet's "No Diggity" clip, and I would've totally believed you. That's just how tunnel-vision-focused I was on my bowl of Totto Spicy Ramen and just how far removed I was from the real world. And quite possibly this decade. I was pretty much face-down in my ramen bowl for a solid, non-stop twenty minutes, mainly due to the following exceptional two components: 1) The Broth - This was such a spectacular base for the entire meal, it could've been a soup all its own at some lesser establishment. Full of fantastic flavor, and with an addictive kick that really transitions nicely into a wonderful aftertaste (as advertised), the chicken-soy sauce broth owes most of its praise to their original rayu (spicy sesame oil), which has been given a two chili pepper rating on their spiciness scale. For reference, the Totto Extra Spicy Ramen has a nine (!). I bow before those who can tackle this monster. I'll take my measly two peppers and keep my tears, thank you very much. 2) The Char Siu - An especially thick, super-soft slab of salty pork, this is the one ingredient you want to finish entirely once you take that first bite, but know you've got a whole bowl of ramen to consume, so you should probably just submerge it under a bed of noodles so that you can keep re-discovering it. Yes, I played hide-and-seek with my pork. But this wasn't just any pork - this was quite possibly the best char siu I've had served with ramen. And you can quote me on that one. While you will most likely wait roughly an hour during dinnertime to get a table (you must sign yourself up on the clipboard hanging from the door, you must be present when your name is called, and you must have your entire party there or else you get bumped to the bottom of the list), the wait for your food will be minimal once seated. I literally placed my order with the waitress, excused myself to go to the restroom, and when I came back, a giant, steaming bowl of ramen had sat itself before my empty chair. And despite this seemingly Nazi-style set of house rules, it's really to keep everyone on their toes and the line moving, because the staff was totally all smiles inside. With a little En Vogue, Boyz II Men, and (if you're lucky) possibly even a cameo by Bell Biv DeVoe accompanying some of the absolute best ramen in the city, you'd be smiling, too.
