Since the Serious Eats review, expect to wait up to an hour for a seat at Totto Ramen. The restaurant is small, with less than a dozen bar stools and a few tables in the back. Unfortunately, coming solo won't guarantee that you'll get seated first. It's first come, first serve, and the staff will usually wait for an entire section to clear so that they can seat that 5-person party that came two minutes before you. Still, true to its character, turnover is really quick and the spare menu ensures that people will immediately know what to order. A fast as your steaming bowl of ramen is prepared, you will devour it in minutes. Most diners are in and out within 20 minutes so the wait passes by pretty quickly. Still- it's worth it. There are five or six types of ramen, including two spicy ones and two vegetarian ones. I ordered the highly acclaimed chicken paitan, which comes with the most perfect al dente noodles you can imagine. Despite the fact that its a chicken stock (and your only options are a chicken or a vegetable stock), the broth is every bit as rich and flavorful and as sweet and fatty as you can hope. Each bowl comes with two slices of char siu, which, if you sit at the bar, you can watch the chefs broil using a mini flame torch. These slices are thin and extra fatty and will literally melt in your mouth. Perfection in broth, noodles, and quality of toppings! If its your second time here, be sure to try the miso ramen. This miso ramen is unlike any I've ever had before. I'm usually accustomed to my miso being lighter than the tonkotsu base, but this miso is heavy, heavy, heavy, and every bite delicious. The noodles are wavier and- surprisingly- more firm and chewy than the chicken paitan noodles. I love that it comes with half of a seasoned boiled egg, char siu, and a scoop of ground pork. ?The broth is also more acidic, with a bit of a bite. Still, its strangely addictive and the flavor never gets repetitive. You will be tempted (like we were) to call out "kaedama!" and get another ball of perfectly cooked noodles to throw in whatever left over broth you have. Generous portions, terrific servers, and five-star food in the most casual, no-frills environment. The prices are also really really reasonable, arguably even cheap in this ramen-fad city (the chicken paitan is reasonably under $10-- ramen should not cost you $15!). Yes, I think it is WAY better than Ippudo (which I never thought was worth the wait). And yes, it is LIGHTYEARS better than Momofuku (which has pretty weak broth and noodles, that even the off-the-hook toppings can't compensate for). Come for dinner or even a weekday lunch and you won't be disappointed. Hit up Ippudo if you want to seat a large group, since you shouldn't even think about bringing a party of more than four or five here. Honestly, this is the bowl of ramen I have been waiting for my entire life!
