I believe there is a ramen war going on in NYC, as with the pizza wars, the ramen wars are heating up. As of late these small, unimposing, and severely delicious restaurants seem to be popping up everywhere. You have your upscale - Momofuku & Ippudo and then your more traditional ones Hide Chan & Totto Ramen. The question is ... who makes the best? As always, I believe those answers are mostly subjective. What you do get from Totto Ramen is an incredible bowl of almost perfectly made ramen with fresh noodles, succulent pork, a spicy kick and the atmosphere of a real "Salary Man's" ramen joint in Japan. It's most likely that you WILL wait up to an hour to get a seat here at Totto Ramen and believe me, it's absolutely worth it. Cramming 10-20 people in a basement, bench style restaurant is how most of these restaurants function in places like Tokyo & Osaka. Stepping foot into this establishment brought me back to my trip to Japan over a year ago and that cozy, intimate and (let's be honest) drunk as a skunk experience... and I loved every moment. The waitress was sweet, the host was kind, the cooks looked like they genuinely loved what they were doing and everything was cooked and displayed out in front of us within minutes, nay... seconds. Their prices are excellent, the service swift and the drinks abundant. Our group chowed down on the regular Totto Spicy Ramen and the "Rice Sandwich" which is a staple in most Asian countries. Everything was superb, I left feeling full and fulfilled. The ingredients were fresh and the soup was hearty. I would've preferred a little less salt, but let's face it.. it's ramen.. it's going to be salty. Besides, that's what my Sapporo and bottle of Soju was for!!! So hunker down, put yourself on the list and cram yourself into this establishment before all the tourists get wind of it. It's definitely worth the spice-induced coma you will most likely have walking out of it.
