This is the most awesomest ramen place I've ever been to! Granted, I haven't tried Hide-chan or Ippudo yet... but I love Totto Ramen! We got a bunch of stuff, so here's a breakdown. Look at my pictures to see what each of these look like! 1. Chicken Paitan. I was soooooo freaking impressed with the broth! I've never been fanatic about tonkotsu, even though I think it's really tasty. There's just something really hearty about a chicken-y broth, especially on a cold windy NY evening. The broth is really really rich, almost richer than you anticipate chicken broth to be. It's thick and full of flavor! If you sit at the bar, you can see the chef making broth (with a big paddle) for the next couple of days! The chicken paitan comes with 2 slices of pork, minced pork, scallion and a piece of nori. The noodles are also different from other ramen places. It's straight, not curly and had a nice bouncy texture. Yummmmmm! 2. Spicy Ramen. For those who like spice, this is a great choice. Though I would advise spice-lovers to still get the chicken paitan and get a side order of the spicy rayu oil. You'd want to taste the chicken paitan broth on its own first. Then add all the spice you want! 3. Tuna Zuke Don. This was one of the specials on the wall (thank goodness I read Japanese, lol!). I think it was for $4.50, which is a great deal considering you get a huuuuuge piece of tuna over a bowl of rice with tobiko, chopped onoin, slices of nori, cucumber, scallion, sesame seeds, wasabi, and a special sesame sauce which was deeeeeelicious! 4. Mushroom Takikomi Gohan. This is a great rice dish that I love to get at Japanese restaurants. Usually it involves steaming various vegetables (like mushroom) with the rice in a clay pot. I don't know how Totto Ramen does it (but Yakitori Totto brings it to you in a clay pot), but it's delicious! The rice becomes so flavorful with the veggies - you can smell the fragrance! 5. Pork Yuzu-Mayo Don. This is on the regular menu, I think. Basically you get two pieces of blow-torch seared pork over a bowl of rice with a yuzu-mayo sauce. I personally think the mayo is overpowering because the pork is already so rich. The yuzu definitely helps. I wish this rice bowl came with a thinner, grease-cutting sauce. It was, nonetheless, delicious though! The wait for Totto Ramen is infamous, but I actually didn't think it was too bad. Even if there are 10-15 waiting in front of you, you'll get in relatively quickly (compared to other restaurants), because Totto Ramen's turnover is so fast. They serve you within minutes! Sitting at the bar is a must. You get to see all the action before you eat! It's really awesome :)
