After being impressed with Ippudo a couple weeks back, my girlfriend and I have decided to check out some of the other ramen shops in the city. Given that she's not a big fan of MSG, we decided to hit up Totto next (they have a nice big sign in the front window that says no MSG). It was a bit of a haul up to the Theater District from Murray Hill, and it was pretty chilly to be waiting outside for a spot (there's no room inside to wait, so if you're going to trek out in the winter, head to the Starbucks on 8th Avenue while you wait or wear lots of layers). It was around 9 PM on a Saturday night, but we got in 30 minutes or so. There's a bar with 10 spots, along with a few tables, so it's probably not the greatest idea to come with a group. The menu is straightforward - there are a few different types of basic ramen, along with various sides you can add into the broth. I ended up getting the chicken paitan, while my girlfriend tried the miso base. I also got a soft-boiled egg and a seasoned avocado (which worked very well in the broth). I also got a pork rice ball, which was delicious but not anything too out of the ordinary. The ramen, though, was worth the wait. I'm not sure how the broth is prepared - aside from the fact they have two or three giant vats full of broth going at all times - but it was so rich with chicken flavoring. The noodles were cooked very well - just right, and not too soft so that they were soggy. I'm a bigger fan of the pork at Ippudo, mainly because I'm a sucker for braised pork belly that shamelessly displays its fattiness, but the pork here was pretty decent too...aside from the fact you get to see it cooked (aka blowtorched) right in front of you. You also get less meat in the bowl, which was disappointing but not that bad, since it's not the main part of any ramen dish. All in all, we finished up in about 40 minutes, all warmed up and ready to face the cold weather. Make sure to bring cash to pay, but aside from that, this is a very nice