verly dried, like what you get with instant noodles). I feel Ippudo just has theirs a shade better. ?But we are really splitting hairs of ramen here, you won't tell the difference in a blind taste test. Because I am not blind (except in love), verdict = Ippudo 5) Char Siew (the pork slices): you see one of the cooks painstakingly grilling the char siews with a mini blowtorch, browning them here and sizzling them there. Quite in the genre of Yakitori Totto (see my other review), where they turn and prod the skewers the way you and I handle a newborn. The outcome is meat that is done just right - texture that is neither rubbery (sign of overcooked) or raw (unclean for pork), with the right amount of residual fat, dripping with juices neither too salty or savoury. Verdict = Totto 6) Egg: Fundamental in any good ramen is the egg. I spent hours in my amateur kitchen trying to get that solid-on-the-outside-runny-on-the-inside egg necessary to complement a good ramen. Ippudo does this to perfection, a proper poached egg. Totto does this as a boiled egg. Verdict = Ippudo 7) Price: For the difference in dollars it doesn't make a material difference, but it can add up. For example, the Miso Ramen at Totto is $10; at Ippudo it's $13. 2 pieces of char siew topping cost $2 at Totto; $3 for Ippudo. The egg is $1 at Totto; $2 at Ippudo. In this 10% unemployment economy, every buck counts. Verdict: Totto ? Bottom line: A carnivore may prefer Totto. A purist may demand Ippudo. A New Yorker probably won't give a damn.
