Totto Ramen is the one ramen shop to rule them all. If you want simple ramen, go to the dozens of others in the St. Marks area, but if you want amazing, I can't believe ramen could be so good, come to Totto Ramen. And when you get there, make sure to immediately sign the board at the bottom of the steps, which serves as the waiting list. The steps leading down to Totto Ramen serves as the waiting area, with an enclosed plastic canopy to protect you from the elements and colder weather. If you are called and you're not there, they will bump you back to the bottom of the list. Parties of 4 are the maximum at a table, anything larger will be split up. My personal recommendation is to come with one other person or come solo, to be seated the quickest. When you make it in, you'll know exactly why, as there are only 10 stools at the bar, one 2-person table, and two 4-person tables. When you're finally seated, a cup of water and menu is standing on the table waiting for you. If you already had a chance to look at the menu by the entrance, good for you! Otherwise peruse the short menu or take a look at the specials plastered on the walls. When you're ready, raise your hand to get the attention of the waiter. In a few minutes, your order will be brought to you. I ordered the Totto Spicy Ramen ($10.75) which is their original homemade Paitan Ramen noodles and Original Rayu, which is a spicy sesame oil, that adds a spicy kick to an otherwise amazing ramen dish already. It is then topped with scallion, char siu pork, bean sprouts and nori (seaweed). There's so many words to describe the broth: divine, savory, rich, and most of all it's clean in the respect that it's not muddled down from the starchiness of the noodles and other ingredients. The homemade ramen noodles were amazing, albeit slightly chewy, did a great job absorbing the flavors of the broth. The char siu pork was fatty, tender, and very flavorful. Part of the that was the from the nice char that was created on it from the handheld blow torch. And back to that spicy sesame oil, unbelievably simple to add yet so delicious. That extra layer of flavor and heat, definitely upped the likability of this ramen dish tenfold. But if you don't like spicy food, their Original Paitan Ramen is just as delicious. If there is anything to dislike about this place, it may be NYC's Department of Health restaurant inspection, which gave it a C rating. I agree somewhat, as all of their food is sitting around. If you sit by the bar, you will have the chance to watch the staff work their magic, but you may find some of their methods a bit unhygienic. The huge pots of broth and the metal containers with ingredients (scallion, bean sprout, nori, etc.) are sitting less than 5 feet away from you with tops opened and exposed to whatever may fall in it. The char siu pork is sitting in an open-faced buffet tray on a top shelf near the ceiling, which doesn't look the most sanitary. When an order comes in, they simply pull the tray down, take out some pieces of the char siu pork and place it on a cooling rack. They then whip out their handheld blow torch and torch the pork to give it a nice char. When they were refilling one of the huge pots of broth, I also noticed one of the staff had sneezed. He had attempted to cover his mouth with his arm, but you could see that his arm had only got up to cover half of his sneeze. It's worth noting that he wasn't facing the pot of broth. He was turned sideways, but on one side, he had all the open pots, and on the other side, you have all the customers sitting at the bar. And if you need to use the bathroom, I recommend avoid using it here as it is the tiniest bathroom I've ever been to. There's barely any standing room in there, with the toliet on one side, and the small sink hitting you on the waist from the other side. Maybe that small ounce of dinginess could scare some customers away. But that didn't really phase me as I can overlook that and claim that Totto Ramen has one of the best ramen I've ever had. I'm salivating just thinking about this place. Prices are a lot cheaper than some more reputable places like Ippudo and portions are decent. Just remember to bring cash, as they only accept cash, no credit. If you can get over the wise-tale that ramen shops are simply no more than instant noodles (aka Maruchan), or are simply a ramen fanatic, Totto Ramen is where it's at. Unbelievably so good that I can't wait to come back again and again.
