Totto ramen Tottora men Totora men Totoro men Totoro noodles? Grin. No longer able to avoid its magnetic pull for ramen-goers in the city, Scott and Mike decide to let natural forces do their thing and draw them in to eat some ramen. Of all the places I've been to so far, Totto has the most ramen-ya feel to it: a narrow space only a few feet wider than I am tall, dominated by a long bar along which customers are quickly tossing back bowls of ramen with quick flicks of their wrists. The dcor is an afterthought, if it exists at all, which should be the aim of every good ramen bar. We started with an appetizer of seared tuna served over a bed of bean sprouts with sliced avocado and minced garlic. This was good, but not exceptional. Unfortunately Totto doesn't have tonkotsu on its menu, breaking my streak yet again, so I opted for the chicken paitan ramen while Scott ordered the miso. The paitan broth is a chicken/soy mixture; a little murkier and more textured than plain chicken stock, but nothing out of this world. At first the noodles were al dente, but by one to two minutes in they had already flip-flopped like a politician between a primary and a general election and gone soft. I know the laws of ramen thermodynamics are incredibly complex to even the most seasoned ramen veterans, but you'd think a ramen rocket scientist would be able to figure out how to make and cook noodles such that they could survive in broth for at least five minutes. They were also straight, which always makes me a little sad inside. The pork, however, was great. Although the shape is different from what you'll get at most ramen joints - more rectangle than oval - the meat is every bit as tender and as evenly distributed with fat as what you'll find at the best places. The remaining toppings were mostly standard. The miso ramen followed suit accordingly, save for the clump of miso that was served sitting atop the broth. Totto is a tiny place and it doesn't take reservations, so if you arrive fashionably late you can expect a wait of about an hour. Better to play it safe and get there squarely before 7 pm. If you come on a scorching summer day be prepared find it almost as sweltering inside as it is outside. To Totto's credit it's one of the few places that serves a decent bowl of ramen for under $10. It's ridiculous that I need to flag this when talking about ramen, but such is the New York scene. Totto left us satisfied, but puzzling over why it is hailed as one of the best ramen shops in the city as we returned to scouting out the remaining locations on our quest. In the meantime weekly ramen continues its pilgrimage along the manifold path to noodle soup nirvana.
