I first tried to eat at Totto Ramen for dinner last Saturday. We put our name down on the list hanging from the door, and after waiting half an hour, we still weren't seated. We asked how much longer the wait would be and were told that it would be about 40 minutes more. Since we had a Broadway show to catch after dinner, we decided to go somewhere else for dinner. Fast forward two days later. My sister and I tried again on Labor Day, and as expected there was a wait. I guess it's not hard to be popular when the food is good and your restaurant only seats 18 people max. This time we lucked out and we were seated within 30 minutes. We started with the Labor Day special, RA MUSUBI (Japanese rice ball). At this point we were starving so the rice ball was the perfect size appetizer and had us anticipating our ramen. http://www.yelp.com/biz_ My sister and I love spicy food, so we both opted for the TOTTO EXTREME SPICY RAMEN. http://www.yelp.com/biz_ The Extreme had the appeal of 9 chili peppers next to it's name on the menu, while the Totto Spicy Ramen only had 2 chili peppers. When the ramen arrived, there was spicy sauce in the bowl but we were also given some extra spicy sesame oil sauce on the side (how thoughtful!). I usually prefer tonkotsu broth with my ramen, but Totto's signature chicken broth was very satisfying with the spicy sesame oil mixed it. The three thin slices of pork were perfectly fatty and tender and the noodles were al dente. I liked the addition of bean sprouts, which I don't usually see in ramen, but provided a good break from the spiciness. Even if you can handle spicy, I wouldn't dump all of the extra sauce in the bowl. Instead I recommend adding some sauce to each bite of noodles. That way you can really taste the spiciness and flavor of the sauce and you're not left with undrinkable soup at the end of the meal. All in all, I think Totto Ramen does a good job of standing out from the other top ramen places in the city. I like that their spicy 