I came to Totto Ramen in the hopes of finding gourmet ramen as good as Ippudo's (or close) with half the wait at a more convenient location. Unfortunately I only scored 1 out of 3 of those here. When I stumbled upon Totto Ramen for the first time on a Saturday night, the wait was an hour and a half. I passed it up but decided to return since good things come to those who wait. Apparently not in this case. On another Saturday night, I only endured a 40 minute wait but time seems to pass exponentially slower when waiting outside in the cold without a 2 for 1 Sapporo happy hour. Inside, Totto Ramen is reminiscent of what actual ramen shops look like in Japan - a spattering of small tables packed tight next to a ramen bar where hot noodles are served up to order. Now this isn't necessarily a bad thing but it's definitely different than the faux modern japanese decor at Ippudo. When you walk in you know ramen at Totto is served quick with no frills. I had high hopes for the ramen here, but I found myself seriously disappointed. Ramen here is served with one of two broths - a chicken stock or a mushroom stock (for vegetarians mostly). The varieties on the menu basically offer different levels of spiciness plus a miso option. Coming here, I had the preconception that spicy ramen was really just a way to add flavor to a bland base broth but with so many rave reviews I gave it a try. Unfortunately it was exactly what I thought it'd be - a bland broth with a spicy cover up. It was spicy. That's for sure. But it lacked the full richness and flavor that a true pork based broth would have. The same applied to the miso option. It had a bit more flavor because of the miso, but it still couldn't make up for the quality of chicken broth. As for the "extreme spicy" ramen that is supposedly 5x spicier than the spicy ramen according to the menu's chili pepper illustration, I'd rather just down a few habeneros and call it a day. Some people might enjoy the "lighter" chicken broth served