Totto (Chicken Man) Ramen is a little hole in the wall place, like many ramen restaurants in Japan, and an affiliate of Hide-Chan across town. Totto is chicken broth oriented, but they have several varieties to choose from. I've had the regular, the spicy, and the meat lovers' ramen. Beware the meat lovers' (niku ramen)! It has, like, an entire pig in the bowl, which is also extra large, so you are unlikely to need kaedama. I couldn't even finish it all, which must be a first in my dining history. Niku Ramen is really tasty and satisfying, though. The broth just really warms the heart. It's off menu, so you have to ask for it. $15. The other options are fine, too, though I prefer Hide-chan a little bit. At both places, you will probably find the ramen palette-killing salty, as it is traditionally served in the States. Unfortunately, going there requires a trek to the East side. There is almost always a line and a sign-up list at Totto, so you are likely going to wait. If you show up alone, you have a better chance at quickly getting a seat at the bar. Otherwise, be prepared to endure the retarded (literally) new New York dining ritual. I had lunch here yesterday and had to listen to the two guys next to me enthusing about how great the ramen is. I think they wanted to suck the chef's cock, they were carrying on about it so much. So that's a positive review for you. As far as I can tell, the ramen here is totally fine, but it's never going to satisfy a ramen purist who's been to Japan. But nothing can satisfy them. Comparisons to Ippudo, I should add, miss the point entirely.
