After trying, and failing miserably to get into Ippudo for a few weekends, I happened to drive by this little joint by accident one day with my son when we were on our way home from a day in Times Square. We stopped, hoping to get a seat...but at 5:30 on a Saturday, you better have patience and/or be VERY hungry...because you WILL wait. I don't and I wasn't so we left. We did, however go back the very next weekend at 4;30, (they open the doors at 5PM sharp) and we were number two on the list. We decided to sit at the end of the bar, right in front of the GIANT, smoldering cauldren of soup stock simmering on the fire, (BIG MISTAKE...unless you wearing a tank top and shorts). Anyway...the Ramen. One word...MAGNIFICANT!!! The stock was rich, and hearty flavored with supreme umame, the fifth sense of taste, according to the japaneese anyway. The noodles were cooked a teeny, tiny bit on the al dente side for my taste but I suspect if you let it sit for a few minutes...they will soften up. Good luck with that one because as soon as the bowl is presented to you...you wanna get right in, especially on such a cold night...as it was when we went.. The two slices of roast pork are singed by the chef with a blow torch right before they are placed in the bowl. And the whole concoction is sprinkled with a few bits of perfectly fried garlic pieces. All in all, a delicious bowl of asian soup that goes right up there with my all time favorite, Vietnameese beef Pho from Nha Trang. We will definately be going back soon! By the way, the entire staff is wonderfully friendly, and the chef even apoligized to me for the wait when I told him I tried to get in the weekend before and could not. It's OK chef!
